Slice the @apple{1} in half and remove the core. Chop the apple into 1cm chunks and keep to the side for later.

Peel and very finely chop the @garlic clove{2}. In a #bowl{} mix together the @Mexican spice{1}, the garlic, @olive oil{1%tbsp}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a few grinds of @pepper{} for the marinade.

Slice the @pork medallion{250%g} widthways into micro-thin slices. Put the pork into the bowl with the marinade and leave for ~{15%mins}.

Meanwhile, chop the @red cabbage{1/2} in half lengthways through the root. Slice each half lengthways again. See that triangular shaped, white core in each quarter? Chop it out and throw it away. Now slice the cabbage as thinly as possible widthways. And when we say thin, we mean THIN! Chop your @coriander{2}.

In a large bowl (big enough for the cabbage) mix together the @white wine vinegar{1} and @?sugar{1/2%tbsp} until the sugar dissolves. Toss the cabbage in the dressing and keep it to the side for later.

Pre-heat your oven to 100 degrees. Wrap the @super soft whole wheat tortillas{4} in #foil{} or put them on an #ovenproof plate{} and cover them with another #plate{}. Put them in the oven to warm up while you cook your pork.

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once it's hot add in the pork and cook it for around ~{4%mins} until it is just cooked through. (We took ours out while there was still a little hint of pink left in the middle). If you only have a small frying pan cook the meat in batches so it browns off rather than stews.

> You can make up your tortillas in the kitchen, but we're reckoned it's more fun if you serve your tortillas, fresh coriander, pork, red cabbage, apple chunks and yoghurt in bowls and let everyone tuck in at the table!

Serve with @Greek style natural yoghurt{1/2}.